{{Infobox building |name = Bill & Bobbie Irvine |image = Bill Bobbie.jpg | caption = Bill & Bobbie Irvine }} '''Bill''' (30 January 1926 &ndash; 13 February 2008) '''and Bobbie Irvine''' (27 July 1932 &ndash; 30 May 2004)<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article447218.ece Times Obituary]</ref> were [[United Kingdom|British]] professional [[ballroom dancer]]s. Bobbie Irvine was born Bobbie Barwell in [[Oudtshoorn]], [[South Africa]], while Bill Irvine, born William, was from Low Craigends in [[Kilsyth]]. His father was a miner, as was his grandfather, and Bill served in the [[Royal Navy]] before starting his dance career. As a young dance teacher he spent a period in South Africa, which led to his meeting Bobbie. They were married in 1957.<ref name=irvine>Irvine, Bill & Bobbie 1974. ''The dancing years''.</ref> The pair became South African champions, and later settled in London.
The Irvines won 13 world titles between 1960 and 1968 in the [[World Latin Dance Champions|Professional Latin]] and [[World Ballroom Dance Champions|Professional Modern]] categories of ballroom dancing. Their principal ballroom teachers were Eric Hancox, [[Len Scrivener]] and [[Sonny Binnick]]. They were coached in the Latin dances by [[Nina Hunt]], who became a great friend of the couple.<ref name=irvine/>
{{quote|The Irvines are perhaps the most outstanding couple we have ever had in the profession because they have done well over both branches [ballroom and Latin] and maintained their standard over a number of years. They are good ambassadors for Britain, good teachers, good lecturers, good at everything.<ref>Spencer, Frank & Peggy. 1968. ''Come Dancing''.</ref>}}
They were honoured for their achievements during their careers by appointment as [[Members of the Order of the British Empire|MBE]] in 1967, the first such award made for Latin dancing.<ref>[[Victor Silvester]] was awarded the higher honour of [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] on 1961. In his case, contribution as a musician and as a dancer would have been considered.</ref>
== Competition record == The Irvines' main competitive titles were:<ref name=irvine/>
*1960: World 9 Dance, World Ballroom *1961: World Latin *1962: World 9 Dance; International, British and World Ballroom *1963: World, British Star and International Ballroom; World 9 Dance *1964: World, British and Star Ballroom *1965: World and Star Latin *1966: World, British and Star Ballroom *1967: World and Star Ballroom *1968: Star Ballroom; World Ballroom; World Latin
