'''Bir Bhadra Thapa''' or '''Birabhadra Thapa''' ({{lang-ne|वीरभद्र थापा}}) was a politician, courtier and military officer in the [[Gorkha Kingdom]] during the 18th century. His grandson [[Bhimsen Thapa]] went on to become the [[Mukhtiyar]] of Nepal and founder of [[Thapa dynasty]].

==Career==
When King [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]] annexed [[Nuwakot District|Nuwakot]] in 1744, he was one of the influential Bharadars.{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=22}} After the conquest of Naldum area, he along with Commander [[Shivaram Singh Basnyat]] conquered Sanga, [[Panauti]], [[Sankhu]] and adjacent areas.{{sfn|Khatri|1999|p=18}} The Gorkhali chronicle states that he was the commander of the Gorkhali forces.{{sfn|D.R. Regmi|1975|p=129}} He commanded the Gorkhali troops during the capture of [[Kavrepalanchok District|Kavre]] and [[Kavrepalanchok District|Palanchowk]] with fellow commanders ''Chautariya'' Daljit Shah and ''Kaji'' Harka (Harsh) Pantha.{{sfn|Hamal|1995|p=179}} He was deployed to Kaski allowing two [[Brahmin]]s from there to reside in Kathmandu as a part of friendly diplomacy with Kaski Kingdom.{{sfn|D.R. Regmi|1975|p=253}} He commanded troops near the hill in Sindhuli against the English advance of Major Kinloch.{{sfn|Mahler|1999|p=120}}

==Personal Life==
He belonged to [[Bagale Thapa]] clan that migrated eastwards from [[Jumla district|Jumla]].{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=22}} As per the [[Sardar]]i annual re-instatement letter of his youngest son [[Amar Singh Thapa (born 1759)|Amar Singh Thapa (sanu)]] on Chaitra 1855 B.S., he was said to be a son of '''Bikram Thapa of Bagale clan of Gorkha'''.{{sfn|Acharya|1967}} while as per ''Thapa genealogy'', he was said to be grandson of Bikram Thapa and son of Bijay Thapa.{{sfn|Acharya|1967}}{{sfn|Thapa|1991}} 

He was the patron of leading Thapa [[Chhetri]] group (i.e. [[Thapa dynasty]]) in the Royal Court.{{sfn|Regmi|1995|p=44}} He had three sons; Jeevan Thapa, Bangsha Raj Thapa and [[Amar Singh Thapa (born 1759)|Amar Singh Thapa (sanu)]]. His eldest son died in the [[Battle of Kantipur]] with powerful Kaji [[Kalu Pande]]. The seven sons of Amar Singh Thapa (sanu) - [[Bhimsen Thapa]], [[Nain Singh Thapa]], [[Bhaktabar Singh Thapa|Bakhtawar Singh Thapa]], Amrit Singh Thapa and [[Ranabir Singh Thapa]], all participated and contributed in the expansion and [[Unification of Nepal|unification of Nepal]].{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|pp=22-23}}

