'''Mary Kees''' was the first woman in the United States to take out a [[patent]] in 1808.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YVsDAAAAYAAJ&pg=PR2&lpg=PR2&dq=Mary+Kees+inventor&source=bl&ots=nI2_5gN8DI&sig=Nlou3VQDCuMVgrVM_94AOdiwN3Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj3yd_s1r_cAhXM2FMKHUOwCOEQ6AEwD3oECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Mary%20Kees%20inventor&f=false|title=Womanhood|last=Ballin|first=Ada S.|date=1900|publisher=Womanhood|language=en}}</ref> She invented a technique for weaving straw with silk or cotton thread.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lo5IAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA547&lpg=PA547&dq=Mary+Kees+inventor&source=bl&ots=BPRj8wdNeo&sig=0iINtcxnE-jah1u7bbkCmY6AWU0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj3yd_s1r_cAhXM2FMKHUOwCOEQ6AEwDXoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Mary%20Kees%20inventor&f=false|title=Brotherhood of Locomotive Firemen and Enginemen's Magazine|date=1899|publisher=[[Brotherhood of Locomotive Firemen and Enginemen]]|language=en}}</ref>

