{{Spanish name|Hernández|Lechuga}} {{Infobox criminal | name = Raúl Lucio Hernández Lechuga | image_name = | image_size = | image_alt = | image_caption = Raúl Lucio Hernández Lechuga | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Mexico]] | death_date = | death_place = | cause = | alias = ''El Lucky'',<ref>[http://www.abc.es/20111213/internacional/abci-captura-lucky-201112130053.html ''Capturan a «El Lucky», uno de los fundadores del cártel de Los Zetas: El presidente mexicano, Felipe Calderón, informó a través de su cuenta de Twitter de la detención de Raúl Lucio Fernández Lechuga, «El Lucky».''] Manuel M. Cascante. 13 December 2011. Retrieved 8 March 2012.</ref> ''Z-16'' | motive = | charge = [[Drug trafficking]], [[money laundering]], | conviction = | conviction_penalty = | conviction_status = Incarcerated | occupation = [[Los Zetas]] founder | status = Captured | spouse = | parents = | children = }}
'''Raúl Lucio Hernández Lechuga''',<ref>{{cite web|title=ARMADA ASEGURA A RAÚL LUCIO HERNÁNDEZ LECHUGA, ALIAS "EL LUCKY" O "Z-16″|url=http://www.presidencia.gob.mx/2011/12/personal-de-la-armada-de-mexico-asegura-en-veracruz-a-uno-de-los-presuntos-delincuentes-mas-buscados-por-el-gobierno-federal/|publisher=Secretaría de Marina (SEMAR).|accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref> alias ''El Lucky'' and ''Z-16'', is a former [[Mexican people|Mexican]] [[drug lord]] and one of the original founders of the criminal group [[Los Zetas]].<ref>{{cite news|title='El Lucky', presunto fundador de 'Los Zetas', es detenido por la Marina|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/12/12/el-lucky-presunto-fundador-de-los-zetas-es-detenido-por-la-marina|accessdate=13 December 2011|newspaper=CNN Mexico|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111213061228/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/12/12/el-lucky-presunto-fundador-de-los-zetas-es-detenido-por-la-marina|archivedate=13 December 2011|df=}}</ref> The government of Mexico had listed Hernández Lechuga as one of its 37 most wanted drug lords and offered the equivalent of over $2 million [[USD]] for information leading to his capture.<ref>[http://noticias.univision.com/mexico/noticias/article/2009-03-23/mexico-ofrece-millonarias-recompensas-por?page=2 Univision. ''México ofrece millonarias recompensas por 37 líderes del narco''.] English title: Mexico offers rewards in the millions for 37 drug lords. Retrieved 18 February 2011.</ref>
==Kingpin Act sanction== On 24 March 2010, the [[United States Department of the Treasury]] sanctioned Hernánez Lechuga under the [[Foreign Narcotics Kingpin Designation Act]], sometimes referred to simply as the "Kingpin Act", for his involvement in drug trafficking along with fifty three other international criminals and ten foreign entities.<ref>{{cite web|title=DESIGNATIONS PURSUANT TO THE FOREIGN NARCOTICS KINGPIN DESIGNATION ACT|url=http://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/Programs/Documents/narco_designations_kingpin.pdf|publisher=[[United States Department of the Treasury]]|accessdate=28 May 2014|page=11|date=15 May 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514025153/http://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/Programs/Documents/narco_designations_kingpin.pdf|archivedate=14 May 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref> The act prohibited U.S. citizens and companies from business activities with him, and froze all his assets in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|title=An overview of the Foreign Narcotics Kingpin Designation Act|url=http://www.assetsearchblog.com/uploads/file/drugs.pdf|publisher=[[United States Department of the Treasury]]|accessdate=28 May 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140528053616/http://www.assetsearchblog.com/uploads/file/drugs.pdf|archivedate=28 May 2014|page=1|date=2009}}</ref>
==Arrest== He was apprehended in [[Córdoba, Veracruz]] on 12 December 2011, and was believed to have controlled operations for [[Los Zetas]] in over 10 states in Mexico.<ref>{{cite news|title='El Lucky' dirigía operaciones de 'Los Zetas' en 10 entidades del país|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2011/12/13/el-lucky-dirigia-operaciones-de-los-zetas-en-10-entidades-del-pais|accessdate=13 December 2011|newspaper=CNN Mexico}}</ref> In addition, one of his bodyguards was killed; authorities also found 133 rifles, five grenade launchers, 29 grenades and 36 pistols at the scene of the raid. [[Mexican Navy|SEMAR]] also found bulletproof vests with the letter "Z", the Zetas symbol, on the front.<ref>{{cite news|last=Castillo|first=Eduardo|title=Mexico says captured cartel leader had arsenal|url=http://www.chron.com/news/article/Mexico-says-captured-cartel-leader-had-arsenal-2399474.php|accessdate=14 December 2011|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=13 December 2011}}</ref> After his arrest, Zetas leader Fernando Martínez Magaña (alias "Z-16") took his place in the organization. He was arrested by Mexican law enforcement, however, on 15 May 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Capturan al Z16, líder del narco en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.milenio.com/policia/Estrategia_de_Seguridad_tamaulipas-Fernando_Martinez_Magana-Monte_Alejandro_Rubido_Garcia-violencia-plan_tamaulipas_0_299370350.html|accessdate=16 May 2014|newspaper=[[Milenio]]|date=15 May 2014|language=Spanish}}</ref>
