{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}
{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}
'''William Frederick Elliot Eden''' (19 January 1782 – January 1810) was a [[British people|British]] soldier, politician and [[Member of Parliament#United Kingdom|Member of Parliament]], serving as [[Teller of the Receipt of the Exchequer|Teller of the Exchequer]].<ref name=peerage-WFEE>{{cite web|title=Hon. William Frederick Elliot Eden|url=http://thepeerage.com/p3491.htm#i34910|publisher=The Peerage|accessdate=10 June 2011|date=28 January 2011}}</ref>

==Life==
Born into the influential Eden family, one of fourteen children, William was the eldest son of [[William Eden, 1st Baron Auckland|William Eden]], later to become the 1st Baron of Auckland, and his wife Eleanor Elliot, daughter of [[Sir Gilbert Elliot, 3rd Baronet, of Minto|Sir Gilbert Elliot, 3rd Baronet]].<ref name=links>{{cite web|title=Hon. William Frederick Elliot EDEN|url=http://genealogy.links.org/links-cgi/readged?/home/ben/camilla-genealogy/current+c-eden9398+2-2-0-1-0|publisher=Links - Genealogy|accessdate=10 June 2011}}</ref>

==Career==
Eden became MP for [[Woodstock (UK Parliament constituency)|Woodstock]] in the [[United Kingdom general election, 1806|1806 general election]], the same constituency as his father had represented. In the same year he was given the position of [[Teller of the Receipt of the Exchequer]].

Eden was also a [[Lieutenant-Colonel]] in the [[85th Regiment of Foot (Westminster Volunteers)|Westminster Volunteers]].

==Death==
The drowned body of Eden was found by a [[barge]]man, William Western, in the [[River Thames]], [[London]], on 25 February 1810. He had been missing since 19 January. Although he was thought to have committed [[suicide]] on that day, the inquest jury returned a verdict of "Found drowned in the river, but by what means it came there, there was no evidence before the Jury." William Western received £50 for finding the body.
His brother, [[George Eden, 1st Earl of Auckland|George Eden]], succeeded their father in the [[Baron Auckland|Auckland Barony]]. William Eden was unmarried.

